Quote:  The foot of the <i>pekerangi,</i> about 15 feet high, was strengthened with a facing of rocks and [42] stones ...; this was a variation of the usual Maori method of leaving the foot of the <i>pekerangi</i> open for the garrison's fire. ibid. 51-52 The outer wall, the <i>pekerangi</i>, or curtain, was formed of stout timbers ... sunk deeply in the ground at short intervals, with saplings and split timbers closely set between the larger posts, all bound firmly [52] together with cross-rails and <i>torotoro</i>, or bush-vines
